    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"goblin of the decimal\" is just a colloquialism, a way of describing the cumulative effect of small errors that can add up over time. But, I digress.\n\nFrom a technical standpoint, a system error could cause discrepancies between the physical count and the digital log in several ways. For example, if the inventory management system is not properly synchronized with the warehouse's inventory management system, it's possible that the digital log is not being updated in real-time. This could result in a discrepancy between the physical count and the digital log, especially if the physical count is updated manually.\n\nAnother possibility is that the inventory management system is using a \"goblin of the clock\" – a timing issue that causes the system to lag behind the physical count. For instance, if the system is only updated every hour, and the physical count is updated every 15 minutes, the digital log will be behind the physical count, resulting in a discrepancy.\n\nIn the case of the SKUs you provided, it's possible that the discrepancy is due to a software issue that's causing the system to miscount or misreport the quantity of each item. For example, if the system is using a \"goblin of the rounding\" – a rounding",
